I've now seen all the new hymns sung at least once in my dataset. <hymn>Let Easter Anthems Ring (#1205)</hymn> is high on this list, but that's only because of [Easter](/posts/easter2025). It looks like <hymn>Softly and Tenderly Jesus Is Calling (#1020)</hymn> is currently the most popular of the new hymns generally. It's followed by <hymn>This Little Light of Mine (#1028)</hymn> and then <hymn>I Know That the Savior Loves Me (1021)</hymn>, but we'll likely see this change a little bit over the next few weeks and months. 

(For a complete version of this table that includes all hymns, see [here](/overview.qmd).)

## What hymns are most popular each week?

It's been long enough that we can get an idea of which hymns were popular when. The following plot shows the percentage of wards that sang each hymn *of the wards that sang any third batch hymns*. 



::: {.cell .column-page}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=1248}
:::
:::



It seems like the most popular hymns are somewhat erratic: <hymn>Softly and Tenderly Jesus Is Calling (#1020)</hymn>, <hymn>I Know That My Savior Loves Me (#1021)</hymn>, and <hymn>This Little Light of Mine (#1028)</hymn> jump around a lot for some reason. It's possibly a sample size issue, because relatively few wards are singing them. Some of the less common ones don't show a clear pattern, other than they're generally present but not common. Some become slightly more popular after a few weeks, again suggesting (like the other batches) that once wards have gotten the favorites out of the way, they are then open to trying new ones. The most obvious trend though is <hymn>Let Easter Anthems Ring (#1205)</hymn> and <hymn>Were You There? (#1206)</hymn> being sung around [Easter](/posts/easter2025).

## When during meetings are these hymns sung?

We can now see when during sacrament meetings these hymns have been sung. These results will likely change slightly as more time passes, but it's been long enough and enough data has come in that we can get a good idea of what's going on.



